Rule.desc: Make sure implementation of Object.equals(Object) is reflexive
Do not rely on the write() method to output integers outside the range 0 to 255
Do not modify collection while iterating over it
Avoid NullPointerException
Avoid unvalidated input in array indexes
Avoid division by zero
Do not create multiple buffered wrappers on a single byte or character stream
Do not invoke overridable methods from the readObject() method
Restore prior object state on method failure
Ensure resources are deallocated
Prevent exposure of sensitive data
Protect against Library injection
Protect against Reflection injection
Protect against SQL injection
Protect against XML data injection
Check floating-point inputs for exceptional values
Avoid operating on tainted data in privileged blocks
Remove temporary files before termination
Protect against log forging
Validate all dangerous data
Do not expose data wrapped by a buffer to untrusted code
Do not abandon unreleased locks
Do not use blocking methods while holding a lock
Do not use an instance lock to protect shared static data
Avoid declaring methods to throw general or unchecked Exception types
Avoid using reflection methods
Avoid conversions from parameterized types to raw types
Override 'Object.hashCode()' when you override 'Object.equals()' and vice versa
Avoid using increment or decrement operators in nested expressions
Do not define 'finalize()' method in bean classes
Avoid granting access permission for EJB methods to the 'ANYONE' role
Do not throw exceptions from constructors of "public" non-"final" classes
Do not catch 'NullPointerException'
Do not throw exception types which are too general or are unchecked exceptions
Do not use 'finalize()' methods to unregister listeners
Do not call 'finalize()' explicitly
Ensure that files do not contain cyclical dependencies
Avoid logging sensitive Hibernate-related information at the 'info' level in 'log4j.properties' files
Use the optional java.util.Locale parameter
Do not call 'Character.toLowerCase(char)' or 'Character.toUpperCase(char)' in an internationalized environment
Do not hide inherited "static" member methods
Give "finalize()" methods "protected" access
Provide mutable classes with copy functionality
Close resources as early as possible
Ensure that keys used in comparison operations are immutable
Do not overload the 'finalize()' method
Do not use deprecated APIs
Avoid using 'return's inside 'finally blocks if thare are other 'return's inside the try-catch block
Do not exit "finally" blocks abruptly
Do not use '==' or '!=' to compare objects
Avoid referencing mutable fields
Check the return value of methods which read or skip input
Avoid calculations which result in overflow or NaN
Avoid comparisons to Double.NaN or Float.NaN
Avoid implicit casts from integer data types to floating point data types
Do not pass floating point values to the 'BigDecimal' constructor
Do not use an integer outside the range of [0, 31] as the amount of a shift
Do not cast primitive data types to lower precision
Avoid using compound assignment operators in cases which may cause overflow
Do not use floating point variables as loop indices
Do not use "float" and "double" if exact answers are required
Ensure that dereferenced variables match variables which were previously checked for "null"
Avoid "try", "catch" and "finally" blocks with empty bodies
Avoid control statements with empty bodies
Ensure method and constructor return values are used
Do not use the non-portable 'System.getenv()' method
Do not access the class loader in a web component
Do not compare Class objects by name
Do not stop the JVM in a web component
Enforce returning a defensive copy in 'clone()' methods
Do not pass user-given mutable objects directly to certain types
Do not store user-given mutable objects directly into variables
Inspect 'static' fields which may have intended to be declared 'static final'
Do not log confidential or sensitive information
Do not pass exception messages into output in order to prevent the application from leaking sensitive information
Inspect instance fields of serializable objects to make sure they will not expose sensitive information
Avoid writing to Consoles
Canonicalize all data before validation
Use wrapper methods to secure native methods
Avoid hard-coding the arguments to certain methods
Avoid using hard-coded cryptographic keys
Avoid passing hardcoded usernames/passwords/URLs to database connection methods
Enforce 'SecurityManager' checks before setting or getting fields
Enforce 'SecurityManager' checks in methods of 'Serializable' classes
Use 'java.security.SecureRandom' instead of 'java.util.Random' or 'Math.random()'
Do not call the 'printStackTrace()' method of "Throwable" objects
Ensure that all Permissions, PrivilegedActions, and PrivilegedActionExceptions are declared in the same package
Use the SSL-enabled version of classes when possible
Make your 'clone()' method "final" for security
Ensure that the 'readObject()' and 'writeObject()' methods have the correct signature
Create a 'serialVersionUID' for all 'Serializable' classes
Avoid re-initializing fields in the 'readExternal()' method of 'Externalizable' classes
Define a "readResolve" method for all instances of Serializable types
Catch all exceptions which may be thrown within Servlet methods
Do not create static variables in a servlet
Do not call the 'run()' method directly on classes extending 'java.lang.Thread' or implementing 'java.lang.Runnable'
Release Locks in a "finally" block
Do not synchronize on constant Strings
Call 'wait()' and 'await()' only inside a loop that tests the liveness condition
Do not use variables of the unsafe type 'java.lang.ThreadGroup'
Do not call the "start" method of threads from inside a constructor
Avoid unsafe implementations of the "double-checked locking" pattern
Ensure that nested locks are ordered correctly
Do not synchronize on "public" fields since doing so may cause deadlocks
Avoid calling unsafe deprecated methods of 'Thread' and 'Runtime'
Do not call 'Thread.sleep()' while holding a lock since doing so can cause poor performance and deadlocks
Do not let "this" reference escape during construction
Inspect accesses to "static" fields which may require synchronization
Make lazy initializations thread-safe
Avoid overriding synchronized methods with non-synchronized methods
Do not synchronize on the class object returned by the 'getClass' method
Make the get method for a field synchronized if the set method is synchronized
Do not call the 'start()' method directly on Thread class instances
Access related Atomic variables in a synchronized block
Do not synchronize on a collection view if the backing collection is accessible
